- when the user asked to review “primarily our CRX Manager folder” and “make sure you have agents.md setup as good as
possible” -> for repo workflow/governance work, compare `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`, hooks, settings, and generated
workflow surfaces instead of answering conceptually [Task 1]
- when the user later said “commit this please” -> once governance changes are validated, be ready to carry them
through a real commit instead of stopping at a plan [Task 1]
- when the user then said “ok push it and merge it” -> default to the full publish flow for that isolated branch:
push, create/update the PR, wait for required checks, and merge if mergeable rather than handing back manual next
steps [Task 1][Task 2]
- the user did not ask for a handoff-only response here, so similar explicitly authorized publish requests should
continue through merge instead of stopping after local verification [Task 2]
- when the user said “Yes create PR I will unlock GitHub later” and later “Ok I turned it in in GitHub co tinie” ->
continue through PR creation once the branch is verified, but keep the work on the feature branch until an explicit
merge/unlock signal arrives [Task 3]

## Reusable knowledge

- In `C:\CRX_Manager`, `AGENTS.md` is now the canonical shared contract, while `CLAUDE.md` is only Claude-specific
routing; future workflow cleanup should preserve that split instead of duplicating shared policy in both files [Task 1]
- The repo-owned verification path for workflow-governance edits is: compare `AGENTS.md`, `CLAUDE.md`,
`.claude/settings.json`, `.claude/hooks/`, `.codex/`, and workflow scripts, then run `node
scripts/agent-health-check.mjs`, `node scripts/check-agent-workflows.mjs`, `npm run test:agent-workflows`, `npm run
check:docs`, `npm run typecheck`, and `npm run lint` [Task 1]
- `node scripts/sync-agent-workflows.mjs --write` and `--check` are the deterministic mirror-sync path; after rebases
or any upstream `.claude` change, rerun the sync before staging because stale `.agents` / `.codex` mirrors and
generated skill copies can otherwise slip through [Task 1]
- `.codex/hooks/production-action-guard.mjs` should emit nothing on allow and JSON only on deny; Codex treated an
explicit allow payload as a failed hook even though the command itself passed [Task 1]
- The real deny-path proof for this repo was `git push --dry-run origin main`, which the PreToolUse guard blocked
before execution with `CRX_PRODUCTION_GUARD_DENIED`; use that instead of assuming the guard works from file inspection
alone [Task 1]
- In isolated CRX workflow-governance worktrees, `npm ci --ignore-scripts` may be required before `npm run typecheck`
and `npm run lint` if dependencies are not installed yet [Task 1]
- The publish run that worked was: rebase onto `origin/main`, verify no existing PR for the branch, push
`codex/agent-setup-20260710`, open PR `#102`, wait for required GitHub checks, then squash merge to `main`; the
resulting merge commit was `40b5b4045c30ff2a2044b93f85086450e61522dd` [Task 2]
- Required checks called out in this rollout included `SQL Migration Validation`, `Lint, Type Check, Test, Build`,
`Analyze (actions)`, `Analyze (javascript-typescript)`, `Analyze (python)`, `CodeQL`, `Vercel`, and `Vercel Preview
Comments`; do not treat an `UNSTABLE` PR as ready while any of those are still pending [Task 2]
- In this repo, `main` is production; GitHub branch protection is the real external boundary, not just a local hook
convention [Task 3]
- The risky classifier for publish/guardrail work must include self-modification surfaces like `.claude/hooks/`,
`.codex/hooks/`, `.github/workflows/`, `.husky/`, and `scripts/run-claude-review.mjs`, not just money/db paths [Task 3]
- The exact-SHA Claude proof model is shared across the Codex and Claude push gates: the proof file must match HEAD
exactly, stay within the 0-30 minute freshness window, and fail closed on future-dated timestamps, BOM, malformed
JSON, wrong SHA, or wrong verdict [Task 3]
- The focused verification suite for this publish family is `node .claude/hooks/codex-push-lib.test.mjs`, `node
.codex/hooks/production-action-guard.test.mjs`, `npm run test:agent-workflows`, `npm run test:correction-guards`, and
`npm run agent-health` before the PR/merge steps [Task 3]
- On this personal GitHub repo, `gh api .../branches/main/protection` must omit org-only `dismissal_restrictions`
fields; required PRs, strict checks, admin enforcement, and force-push/deletion disables were the working shape [Task
3]
- The protected publish sequence that worked was: build and harden the guardrails, fix the follow-up review gap, push
the branch, create draft PR `#114`, mark it ready, merge only after the user unlocks GitHub, then verify Vercel
`Ready` and `https://croprxsolutions.app` HTTP 200; the merged commit was `3cba1f8aa2340686bf5454c9742370ec74d65c6c`
[Task 3]

## Failures and how to do differently

- Symptom: a repo workflow hook looks successful in isolation but Codex treats it as broken. Cause: the allow path
emits output. Fix: keep `production-action-guard` silent on allow and emit structured output only on deny [Task 1]
- Symptom: workflow mirrors or generated skill files drift after a rebase. Cause: upstream `.claude` sources changed
and the generated `.agents` / `.codex` copies were not refreshed. Fix: rerun `node scripts/sync-agent-workflows.mjs
--write`, then rerun the workflow tests before staging [Task 1]
- Symptom: typecheck/lint fail immediately in an isolated worktree that otherwise looks clean. Cause: dependencies
were never installed in that worktree. Fix: run `npm ci --ignore-scripts` before the validation suite [Task 1]
- Symptom: a publish request lands on stale `main`. Cause: the isolated branch drifted behind `origin/main`. Fix:
rebase before pushing and re-run the sync/verification pass afterward [Task 1][Task 2]
- Symptom: a PR looks mergeable but is still not ready. Cause: `gh pr view` may show mergeability while required
checks are still pending and `mergeStateStatus` is not yet clean. Fix: keep polling `gh pr checks --watch` and do not
merge while the PR is `UNSTABLE` [Task 2]
- Symptom: the first commit in an isolated worktree fails before lint/test logic even runs. Cause: dependencies like
`eslint` were never installed there. Fix: run `npm ci --ignore-scripts` before relying on the real pre-commit hook
[Task 3]
- Symptom: a second-model review clears money/db paths but misses a way to weaken the guardrail itself. Cause: the
risky classifier did not treat guard hooks, CI, Husky, or review-wrapper files as risky. Fix: classify
self-modification surfaces up front and cover them in regression tests [Task 3]
- Symptom: the branch-protection API call fails with a 422 on a personal repo. Cause: org-only restriction fields were
included. Fix: retry with the personal-repo-compatible protection payload [Task 3]

