docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:44:The orchestrator reports a fresh complete local gate passed after the latest fixes: forced TypeScript compilation; all 39 regression programs; production build; `npm audit --audit-level=high` with zero vulnerabilities; Deno check for `deliver-grain-alert`; static guards; 9/9 mutation drills; disposable migrations and probes through `0041`; the RLS role matrix; and 32/32 Chromium desktop/phone tests. Independently verify the most relevant evidence rather than merely repeating that claim. Label any command unavailable in the read-only environment as a verification limitation, not a defect.
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:67:Because this candidate includes Supabase SQL, RPCs, RLS, and Edge Functions, I’m using the local Supabase and Postgres-review skills for their audit constraints; I will not contact Supabase or any other provider.
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:79:description: "Use when doing ANY task involving Supabase. Triggers: Supabase products (Database, Auth, Edge Functions, Realtime, Storage, Vectors, Cron, Queues); client libraries and SSR integrations (supabase-js, @supabase/ssr) in Next.js, React, SvelteKit, Astro, Remix; auth issues (login, logout, sessions, JWT, cookies, getSession, getUser, getClaims, RLS); Supabase CLI or MCP server; schema changes, migrations, security audits, Postgres extensions (pg_graphql, pg_cron, pg_vector)."
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:102:> Note that this is separate from RLS, which controls which _rows_ are visible once a table is accessible, not whether the table is accessible at all.
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:104:When a user reports a SQL-created table is unexpectedly inaccessible, check their Data API settings and whether the roles have been granted access via explicit `GRANT` SQL. When granting public (`anon`/`authenticated`) access, always enable RLS too. See [Exposing a Table to the Data API](https://supabase.com/docs/guides/api/securing-your-api.md) for the full setup workflow.
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:106:**5. RLS in exposed schemas.**
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:107:Enable RLS on every table in any exposed schema, which includes `public` by default. This is critical in Supabase because tables in exposed schemas can be reachable through the Data API when the `anon`/`authenticated` roles have access (see [Exposing a Table to the Data API](https://supabase.com/docs/guides/api/securing-your-api.md)). For private schemas, prefer RLS as defense in depth. After enabling RLS, create policies that match the actual access model rather than defaulting every table to the same `auth.uid()` pattern.
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:110:When working on any Supabase task that touches auth, RLS, views, storage, or user data, run through this checklist. These are Supabase-specific security traps that silently create vulnerabilities:
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:113:  - **Never use `user_metadata` claims in JWT-based authorization decisions.** In Supabase, `raw_user_meta_data` is user-editable and can appear in `auth.jwt()`, so it is unsafe for RLS policies or any other authorization logic. Store authorization data in `raw_app_meta_data` / `app_metadata` instead.
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:120:- **RLS, views, and privileged database code**
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:121:  - **Views bypass RLS by default.** In Postgres 15 and above, use `CREATE VIEW ... WITH (security_invoker = true)`. In older versions of Postgres, protect your views by revoking access from the `anon` and `authenticated` roles, or by putting them in an unexposed schema.
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:122:  - **UPDATE requires a SELECT policy.** In Postgres RLS, an UPDATE needs to first SELECT the row. Without a SELECT policy, updates silently return 0 rows — no error, just no change.
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:142:  - **`SECURITY DEFINER` functions bypass RLS.** A `SECURITY DEFINER` function runs with its creator's privileges — typically a role with `bypassrls` (e.g., `postgres`). Never add `SECURITY DEFINER` to resolve a permission error; it silently removes access control without fixing the underlying cause. Prefer `SECURITY INVOKER`.
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:143:  - **`SECURITY DEFINER` functions in `public` are callable by all roles.** Postgres grants `EXECUTE` to `PUBLIC` by default for every new function, so any `SECURITY DEFINER` function in `public` is a public API endpoint callable by `anon` and `authenticated` (which inherit from `PUBLIC`) without any additional grant. When `SECURITY DEFINER` is genuinely needed (e.g., bypassing RLS on an internal lookup table), keep the function in a non-exposed schema, always include an `auth.uid()` check in the function body, and run `supabase db advisors` after making changes.
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:237:- Working with Row-Level Security (RLS)
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:245:| 3 | Security & RLS | CRITICAL | `security-` |
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-11-RUNTIME.stderr.log:280:The Supabase guidance adds two concrete review lenses here: every exposed `SECURITY DEFINER` function must have explicit authentication/authorization plus tightly revoked grants, and RLS must constrain ownership—not merely require the `authenticated` role. The skill’s live-doc lookup is intentionally skipped because your boundary forbids provider contact; I’ll judge the local candidate and flag any genuinely version-dependent point as a limitation.
