docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\TERRA-DELTA-13-RUNTIME.stderr.log:13166:docs/audits/2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review/next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-12-RUNTIME.stderr.log:120:  - **Views bypass RLS by default.** In Postgres 15 and above, use `CREATE VIEW ... WITH (security_invoker = true)`. In older versions of Postgres, protect your views by revoking access from the `anon` and `authenticated` roles, or by putting them in an unexposed schema.
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\TERRA-DELTA-13-RUNTIME.stderr.log:13168:docs/audits/2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review/next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-12-RUNTIME.stderr.log:141:  - **`SECURITY DEFINER` functions bypass RLS.** A `SECURITY DEFINER` function runs with its creator's privileges — typically a role with `bypassrls` (e.g., `postgres`). Never add `SECURITY DEFINER` to resolve a permission error; it silently removes access control without fixing the underlying cause. Prefer `SECURITY INVOKER`.
docs\audits\2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review\next-session-evidence\TERRA-DELTA-13-RUNTIME.stderr.log:13169:docs/audits/2026-07-15-sol-foundation-review/next-session-evidence\SOL-DELTA-12-RUNTIME.stderr.log:142:  - **`SECURITY DEFINER` functions in `public` are callable by all roles.** Postgres grants `EXECUTE` to `PUBLIC` by default for every new function, so any `SECURITY DEFINER` function in `public` is a public API endpoint callable by `anon` and `authenticated` (which inherit from `PUBLIC`) without any additional grant. When `SECURITY DEFINER` is genuinely needed (e.g., bypassing RLS on an internal lookup table), keep the function in a non-exposed schema, always include an `auth.uid()` check in the function body, and run `supabase db advisors` after making changes.
